            "id": "b84fcb0f824c4ae984c6e",
            "questionText": "A metal detector operates using a coil with a cross-sectional area of $!$0.05 \\mathrm{m}^2$!$. When no metal is nearby, the coil generates a magnetic field with a strength of $!$5 \\times 10^{-6} \\mathrm{T}$!$. Upon detecting a buried silver coin, the eddy currents induced in the coin create an opposing magnetic field that reduces the original field within the coil by $!$2 \\times 10^{-7} \\mathrm{T}$!$. Given that the coil has 500 turns, determine the change in magnetic flux linkage through the coil due to the presence of the silver coin.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "760b11a7d1d941dd9cfe2",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by determining the change in magnetic flux per turn. Identify the formula that relates the change in magnetic flux ($!$\\Delta\\Phi$!$) to the cross-sectional area ($!$A$!$) and the change in magnetic field ($!$\\Delta B$!$).",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "a36f52e3-bc9a-40d7-86cc-f5525829e75d"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta\\Phi = A \\times \\Delta B$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta\\Phi = \\Delta B / A$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta\\Phi = A + \\Delta B$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "5baac03014744e4cb248d",
                    "stepText": "Now that you have the flux change per turn, calculate the total change in magnetic flux linkage by multiplying this value by the number of turns in the coil. Provide the numerical answer using the given quantities.",
